From:Madharry
this is probably OT as it relates to this thread but maybe of interest to those
of us long/short financials. I just heard an interview with Benjamin Tal of
CIBC world markets. He impressed me as being a very sharp guy. He is saying
that we have just begun the defaults in the subprime area because we have only
seen the repricing of rates from 2005 in 2007. In 2008 we will see the
repricing of rates from 2006 and the default rates will soar. However this
might be already priced into the derivative markets which are projecting
default rates of 30% over the next 18 months. this level of projected defaults
is unheard of. So the question becomes is this level of defaults already priced
in the prices of financials? (My personal opinion is that they are not).

Mr. Tal anticipates that the fed will be easing rates at a .25 clip early next
year as the defaults rates increase.
(Either way i expect we are going to be seeing loan loss reserves go up
significantly over the next 12 months.)
